    <!-- OCR prep modes explanation -->
    <string name="ocr_explain_prep_modes">Explain recognition modes</string>
    <string name="ocr_prep_modes_title">Recognition modes: simple explanation</string>
    <string name="ocr_prep_modes_message">There are three ways to feed images into the OCR engine:\n\n• Original (no preprocessing) — fastest. We send the photo as-is. Best for already clean, high-contrast scans. May miss faint or noisy text.\n\n• OpenCV Quick — a fast cleanup: convert to grayscale, lightly denoise, make it black/white automatically, and upscale a bit if needed. Good default for most photos. Balanced speed and quality.\n\n• OpenCV Robust — rebuilt for maximum accuracy on difficult pages. It deskews, normalizes shadows/illumination, applies edge‑preserving denoise and smart upscaling. Importantly, it feeds Tesseract a high‑quality grayscale image (not hard black/white) to preserve fine details like loops in “o” and small digits. Best accuracy on tough pages; slower and uses more memory.</string>

